"I1666"},"number_of_marriages":3,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I1672","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":1,"marriage_year":1945},{"spouse_id":"I1673","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":2},{"spouse_id":"I1674","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":3,"marriage_year":1979}],"tags":["author"],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"literature","header":"Nine dark novels, then silence","body":"Between 1950 and 1962 she published nine novels of psychological menace, full of characters with hidden and dangerous second selves, then stopped writing for good. Patricia Highsmith, who almost never reviewed anyone, praised her first book.","number":1},{"category":"literature","header":"An early voice of lesbian pulp fiction","body":"Her frank treatment of gay and lesbian lives made her one of the daring postwar writers who opened American fiction to those themes. Long forgotten, her books were rediscovered and reissued in the early two-thousands.","number":2},{"category":"arts","header":"A debutante who danced in South America","body":"She came out in New York society in 1937, then made her living as a professional dancer in South America and Canada. She gave it up in 1945 to marry an artist and move to Paris.","number":3},{"category":"character","header":"She played down the Roosevelt name","body":"She wrote under her first husband's surname and downplayed her famous lineage, wanting the work judged on its own merits. She married three times and spent her last years alone in the North Carolina woods with cats and chickens.","number":4}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Theodora","last_name":"Roosevelt","display_name":"Theodora Roosevelt Keogh","gender":"female","married_names":[],"bio_blurb":"Roosevelt granddaughter; lesbian pulp-fiction novelist","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781018800/Theo-1948_uucvws.